answers.body_markdown:
**Yes, I agree that the `URI.resolve(URI)` method is incompatible with RFC 3986.** The original question, on its own, presents a _fantastic_ amount of research that contributes to this conclusion.  First, let&#39;s clear up any confusion.

As Raedwald explained (in a now deleted answer), there _is_ a distinction between base paths that end or do not end with `/`:

- `fizz` relative to `/foo/bar` is: `/foo/fizz`
- `fizz` relative to `/foo/bar/` is: `/foo/bar/fizz`

While correct, it&#39;s not a complete answer because the original question is _not asking about a [path][rfc3986-3.3]_ (i.e. &quot;fizz&quot;, above). Instead, the question is concerned with the separate [query component][rfc3986-3.4] of the relative URI reference.  The URI class [constructor used in the example code][URI-ctor] accepts five distinct String arguments, and all but the `queryString` argument were passed as `null`.  (Note that Java accepts a null String as the path parameter and this logically results in an &quot;empty&quot; path component because &quot;[the path component is never undefined][rfc2396-5.2]&quot; though it &quot;[may be empty (zero length)][rfc3986-3.3]&quot;.)  This will be important later.

In an [earlier comment][Sajan], Sajan Chandran pointed out that the [`java.net.URI` class][URI] is documented to implement [RFC 2396][rfc2396] and _not_ the subject of the question, [RFC 3986][rfc3986]. The former was _obsoleted_ by the latter in 2005.  That the URI class Javadoc does not mention the newer RFC could be interpreted as more evidence of its incompatibility.  Let&#39;s pile on some more:

- [JDK-6791060][jdk6791060] suggests this class &quot;should be updated for RFC 3986&quot;.  A comment there warns that &quot;RFC3986 is not completely backwards
compatible with 2396&quot;. It was closed in 2018 as a duplicate of [JDK-8019345][jdk8019345] (still open and unresolved as of October, 2022, with no notable activity since 2013).

- Previous attempts were made to update parts of the URI class to be compliant with RFC 3986, such as [JDK-6348622][jdk6348622], but were then [rolled back][jdk6394131] for breaking backwards compatibility. (Also see [this discussion][jdk-net-dev] on the JDK mailing list.)

- Although the path &quot;merge&quot; logic sounds similar, as [noted by SubOptimal][SubOptimal], the pseudocode specified in the newer RFC does not match the [actual implementation][URI-resolvePath].  In the pseudocode, when the relative URI&#39;s path is _empty_, then the resulting **target path is copied _as-is_ from the base URI**.  The pseudocode&#39;s &quot;merge&quot; logic is not executed under those conditions.  Contrary to that specification, Java&#39;s URI implementation **trims the base path** after the last `/` character, as observed in the question.

There are alternatives to the URI class, if you want RFC 3986 behavior.  Java EE 6 through EE 8 implementations provide [`javax.ws.rs.core.UriBuilder`][UriBuilder], which (in Jersey 1.18) seems to behave as you expected (see below).  It at least claims awareness of the RFC as far as encoding different URI components is concerned.  With the switch from JavaEE to JakartaEE 9 (circa 2020), this class moved to [`jakarta.ws.rs.core.UriBuilder`][ee9UriBuilder].

Outside of J2EE, Spring 3.0 introduced [UriUtils][UriUtils], specifically documented for &quot;encoding and decoding based on RFC 3986&quot;.  Spring 3.1 deprecated some of that functionality and introduced the [UriComponentsBuilder][UriComponentsBuilder], but it does not document adherence to any specific RFC, unfortunately.

[Raedwald]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/27620673/2390644
[Sajan]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22203111/is-javas-uri-resolve-incompatible-with-rfc-3986-when-the-relative-uri-contains#comment43477787_22203111
[SubOptimal]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/27564475/2390644
[rfc3986]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986
[rfc3986-3.3]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-3.3
[rfc3986-3.4]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-3.4

[rfc2396]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2396
[rfc2396-5.2]: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2396#section-5.2

[URI]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/net/URI.html
[URI-ctor]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/net/URI.html#URI%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String%29
[URI-resolvePath]: http://grepcode.com/file/repository.grepcode.com/java/root/jdk/openjdk/8-b132/java/net/URI.java#2006

[UriBuilder]: http://docs.oracle.com/javaee/6/api/javax/ws/rs/core/UriBuilder.html
[ee9UriBuilder]: https://jakarta.ee/specifications/platform/9/apidocs/jakarta/ws/rs/core/uribuilder
[UriUtils]: http://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/util/UriUtils.html
[UriComponentsBuilder]: http://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/util/UriComponentsBuilder.html
[jdk6791060]: https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-6791060
[jdk6348622]: https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-6348622
[jdk6394131]: https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-6394131
