Whenever there are deeply nested classes involved (JAXB, SOAP, JSON, you name it...) and [Law of Demeter][1] isn&#39;t applied, you basically have to check everything and see if there are possible NPEs lurking around.

My proposed solution strives for readibility and shouldn&#39;t be used if there aren&#39;t at least 3 or more nested classes involved (when I say nested, I don&#39;t mean [Nested classes][2] in the formal context). Since code is read more than it is written, a quick glance to the left part of the code will make its meaning  more clear than using deeply nested if-else statements.

